comments.body:
Confirmed with the following configurations that nginx proxy can work with Eucalyptus 3.3:

*HTTP*

{code}
server {
    listen       80;
    error_log /var/log/nginx/walrus-http.log debug;
    server_name  <Walrus DNS Name>; 

    location / {
       proxy_pass http://<ENABLED Walrus IP>:8773/services/Walrus/;
       proxy_buffering off;
       proxy_set_header Host $host;
       proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
       proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
       proxy_connect_timeout   150;
       proxy_send_timeout      100;
       proxy_read_timeout      100;    	   
       proxy_set_header Connection ""; 
    }
}
{code}

*HTTPS*

{code}
server {
       server_name   <Walrus DNS Name>;
       listen 443;
       ssl     on;
       ssl_certificate /etc/nginx/walrus-inmar.crt;
       ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/walrus-inmar.key;
       error_log /var/log/nginx/walrus-https.log debug;

       location / {
               proxy_pass  http://<ENABLED Walrus IP>:8773/services/Walrus/;
               proxy_buffering off;
               proxy_set_header Host $host;
               proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
               proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
               proxy_connect_timeout   150;
               proxy_send_timeout      100;
               proxy_read_timeout      100;
               proxy_set_header Connection "";
       }
}
{code}

The purpose of using a proxy here was to have URLs that didn't have ports or additional service paths added at the end.  For example, instead of
{code}
http://eucalyptus.acme.com:8773/services/Eucalyptus
http://10.20.193.10:8773/services/Eucalyptus
{code}

the following would be seen:

{code}
http://ec2.eucalyptus.acme.com/
{code}

The proxy in this case was an nginx server that handled the re-write of the Walrus URL.  There are 3rd party AWS tools that don't handle ports and additional service paths, so this was the workaround.

Hope this helps.
